      "tex_block": "\\begin{defmark}\n\\begin{Def}[Conditional directed mixed graphs (CDMG)]\n    \\label{def-cdmg}\n    A \\emph{conditional directed mixed graph (CDMG)} $G$---per definition---consists of two (disjoint) sets of\n    vertices (also called nodes):\n    \\begin{enumerate}[label=\\roman*.)]\n        \\item $J$, whose elements are called input nodes,\n        \\item $V$, whose elements are called output nodes,\n    \\end{enumerate}\n%    such that $J \\cup V \\neq \\emptyset$;\n    and two (disjoint) sets of edges:\n    \\begin{enumerate}[resume,label=\\roman*.)]\n        \\item $E \\ins (J \\cup V) \\times V$ the set of directed edges,\n        \\item $L \\ins V \\times V/((v_1,v_2) \\sim (v_2,v_1)) $, the set of bidirected edges, \n        \\item[]    with: $(v_1,v_2) \\in L \\, \\implies\\, v_1\\neq v_2 \\land (v_2,v_1) \\in L$.\n    \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{Def}\n\\end{defmark}",
      "agent_registry": [
        {
          "kind": "for_website",
          "spawned_by": "manager",
          "session_id": "a5115b91-d464-4117-9695-51fff9ebc6b9",
          "first_seen": "2026-06-02T23:23:21+00:00",
          "last_used": "2026-06-02T23:23:21+00:00"
        }
      ],
      "time_needed_to_solve": 2338,
      "addition_to_the_LN": "[l_quotient_vs_ordered_pair_typing_inconsistent] The set $L$ of bidirected edges may be encoded either as a subset of the quotient $V \\times V / {\\sim}$ (with $(v_1, v_2) \\sim (v_2, v_1)$, i.e., as unordered pairs) or as a subset of $V \\times V$ subject to the symmetry constraint $(v_1, v_2) \\in L \\iff (v_2, v_1) \\in L$. Both encodings are admissible; in the ordered-pair encoding, membership of $(v_1, v_2)$ and $(v_2, v_1)$ must always coincide. The irreflexivity condition $v_1 \\neq v_2$ applies under either encoding.\n\n[edge_set_disjointness_under_specified] The qualifier \"disjoint\" applied to the edge sets $E$ and $L$ is to be read as trivial type-level disjointness — directed edges and bidirected edges are objects of distinct types — and imposes no graph-theoretic mutual-exclusion constraint between them. In particular, for $v_1, v_2 \\in V$, it is permitted to have $(v_1, v_2) \\in E$ and $\\{v_1, v_2\\} \\in L$ simultaneously; if a formalization encodes both $E$ and $L$ as subsets of ordered pairs over $V$, the same ordered pair $(v, w)$ may belong to both $E$ and $L$.\n\n[manual_1] Node sets J and V are both finite.",
      "wording_check": {
        "done": true,
        "output": "SUBTLETY:\nid: bidirected_edge_quotient_vs_implication_redundant\nexplanation: The set $L$ is defined as a subset of the quotient $V \\times V / ((v_1,v_2) \\sim (v_2,v_1))$, i.e., elements of $L$ are equivalence classes of ordered pairs identified with their reverses. Under this reading, the equivalence class of $(v_1, v_2)$ literally *is* the equivalence class of $(v_2, v_1)$, so \"$(v_2, v_1) \\in L$\" is automatic whenever \"$(v_1, v_2) \\in L$\".\n\nBut the constraint then states: \"$(v_1,v_2) \\in L \\implies v_1 \\neq v_2 \\land (v_2,v_1) \\in L$\". The conjunct \"$(v_2,v_1) \\in L$\" is redundant under the quotient interpretation — it's already forced by the very definition of $L$.\n\nThis signals one of two things:\n1. The author intended $L$ as a set of *ordered* pairs (not equivalence classes) and the symmetry \"$(v_2, v_1) \\in L$\" is the real constraint, in which case the quotient notation is misleading.\n2. The author intended $L$ as equivalence classes, in which case the symmetry part of the implication is vacuous and only \"$v_1 \\neq v_2$\" carries content.\n\nThe literal text is internally inconsistent in whether elements of $L$ are ordered or unordered. A formalizer must pick one; the choice will leak into every downstream definition that quantifies \"for each bidirected edge $(v_1,v_2) \\in L$\" (does the same edge then also appear as $(v_2, v_1)$, or is each undirected pair encountered exactly once?).\nEND_SUBTLETY\n\nSUBTLETY:\nid: edge_sets_E_and_L_disjointness_ill_typed\nexplanation: The text says \"two \\emph{(disjoint)} sets of edges\" and then defines:\n- $E \\subseteq (J \\cup V) \\times V$ — a set of ordered pairs.\n- $L \\subseteq V \\times V / ((v_1,v_2) \\sim (v_2,v_1))$ — a set of equivalence classes.\n\nThese live in different ambient sets, so on the most literal reading the disjointness condition is either trivially satisfied (a raw ordered pair is never equal to an equivalence class of pairs, so they cannot share an element) or simply ill-typed.\n\nBut the author plainly meant *something* by writing \"(disjoint)\". A plausible intended reading is: for any $v_1, v_2 \\in V$, you cannot have both a directed edge $(v_1, v_2) \\in E$ (or $(v_2, v_1) \\in E$) and a bidirected edge $\\{v_1, v_2\\} \\in L$ between the same two vertices. This is a much stronger and more interesting structural constraint, and standard ADMG-style mixed graphs sometimes do/don't enforce it depending on the author.\n\nThe literal text does not pin this down. A formalizer who takes the strict type-disjointness reading will produce a CDMG type where the same vertex pair can carry both kinds of edge; one who takes the \"no parallel directed+bidirected edge between same pair\" reading will produce a different (and stricter) type. Downstream proofs about, e.g., edge counts or path structure will behave differently.\nEND_SUBTLETY\n\nSUBTLETY:\nid: directed_self_loops_unrestricted_in_E\nexplanation: The definition of the directed edge set is simply \"$E \\subseteq (J \\cup V) \\times V$ the set of directed edges\", with no exclusion of the diagonal. For any $v \\in V$, the pair $(v, v)$ lies in $(J \\cup V) \\times V$, so the literal definition admits $(v, v) \\in E$ — a directed self-loop at $v$.\n\nBy contrast, bidirected edges *do* explicitly forbid self-loops via \"$v_1 \\neq v_2$\".\n\nThis asymmetry — directed self-loops permitted, bidirected self-loops forbidden — is unannotated in the text. In the standard ADMG/CDMG literature directed self-loops are usually excluded (since they trivially break acyclicity and complicate notions like parents/ancestors). If the author intended that exclusion, it has been silently omitted. A literal formalization will allow $v \\to v$, which is likely to surface as an unexpected corner case in any later definition that recurses over directed edges (paths, ancestral sets, topological orderings, d-separation).\nEND_SUBTLETY\n\nSUBTLETY:\nid: empty_vertex_set_admitted\nexplanation: The active text places no nonemptiness condition on the vertex sets. The literal definition therefore admits $J = V = \\emptyset$ (forcing also $E = L = \\emptyset$): the \"empty CDMG\" is a legal CDMG. Whether this degenerate object is intended to be a legitimate inhabitant of the type is unclear from the tex alone. Downstream constructions that, e.g., pick a vertex, take a marginal over a non-empty subset, or assert the existence of a sink/source vertex, will need to either add a hypothesis at the use site or rule out the empty case here. The literal reading leaves this ambiguous.\nEND_SUBTLETY",
        "session": "40652bb0-6f77-4a23-896d-f5b79e85410c"
      }
    },
