      "time_needed_to_solve": 4698,
      "addition_to_the_LN": "[implicit_universal_quantifier_in_hus_clause] The statements \"$j \\hus v \\notin G$\" and \"edges $j \\tuh v$ are allowed\" carry implicit universal quantification over $v$. Precisely: for every $j \\in J$ and every node $v$ in the graph, $j \\hus v \\notin G$; and for every $j \\in J$ and every $v \\in V$, an edge $j \\tuh v$ is permitted in $G$ (its presence is not asserted, only that no restriction forbids it).",
      "wording_check": {
        "done": true,
        "output": "Looking at the tex block, I need to audit the literal wording of this remark explaining the CDMG restrictions.\n\nLet me look at what's actually said:\n1. \"nodes $j \\in J$ will not have any arrowheads pointing towards them: $j \\hus v \\notin G$\"\n2. \"Nodes $j \\in J$ can only point towards nodes $v \\in V$: edges $j \\tuh v$ are allowed\"\n3. \"no two nodes in $J$ are adjacent\"\n\nSUBTLETY:\nid: undirected_edge_between_j_and_v_unaddressed\nexplanation: The remark enumerates three restrictions but leaves the status of an **undirected edge $j - v$** (between a $J$-node and a $V$-node) ambiguous under the literal reading.\n\n- Rule 1 only excludes \"arrowheads pointing towards them\" — an undirected edge $v - j$ has no arrowhead at $j$, so it is *not* excluded by \"$j \\hus v \\notin G$\".\n- Rule 2 says \"Nodes $j \\in J$ can only point towards nodes $v \\in V$: edges $j \\tuh v$ are allowed\". The phrasing \"can only point towards\" restricts the *destination* of arrows leaving $j$, but the colon-clause is permissive (\"are allowed\"), not exhaustive. It does not literally say \"the only kind of edge incident to $j$ is $j \\tuh v$\".\n- Rule 3 governs only $J$-to-$J$ pairs and is silent on $J$-to-$V$ pairs.\n\nThe fact that rule 3 (\"Furthermore, no two nodes in $J$ are adjacent\") is added as a *separate* constraint — not implied by rule 1 — suggests that undirected edges genuinely exist in the CDMG vocabulary (otherwise rule 3 would be redundant with rule 1). This makes the silence about $j - v$ more salient: if undirected edges are a real edge type, then under the literal reading $j - v$ slips through all three rules.\n\nConcrete corner case: take $J = \\{j\\}$, $V = \\{v\\}$, and let $G$ contain a single undirected edge $j - v$. The literal reading of this remark does not flag $G$ as violating any restriction. A downstream claim that \"every edge incident to $J$ is of the form $j \\tuh v$\" (or that $J$ is a set of \"source-only\" nodes) would then not follow from this remark alone.\nEND_SUBTLETY\n\nSUBTLETY:\nid: only_points_to_V_assumes_J_V_disjoint\nexplanation: The sentence \"Nodes $j \\in J$ can only point towards nodes $v \\in V$\" uses \"only\" as a restriction on the destination. The restriction is non-vacuous *only if* $J \\cap V = \\emptyset$ — otherwise (say $J \\subseteq V$, as is common when $V$ denotes the full vertex set in some CDMG conventions), the universal claim \"$j$ points only to elements of $V$\" is automatically true and adds no content.\n\nThe remark cites `\\ref{not-cdmg}` for the notation but does not restate the disjointness (or containment) relationship between $J$ and $V$ in its own text. A reader who interprets $V$ as the full node set will read \"can only point towards $v \\in V$\" as a tautology rather than as the intended restriction \"points to non-$J$ nodes only\". This matters because rule 1 (no arrowheads at $J$) and rule 2 (only-to-$V$) jointly characterize the asymmetric role of $J$, and that characterization quietly depends on which convention `not-cdmg` adopts.\nEND_SUBTLETY\n\nSUBTLETY:\nid: hus_notation_may_not_cover_bidirected_arrowhead_at_j\nexplanation: The prose \"any arrowheads pointing towards them\" is broad — it should cover both a directed edge $v \\to j$ and a bidirected edge $v \\leftrightarrow j$ (both have an arrowhead at $j$). However the formal example given for this restriction is the single expression \"$j \\hus v \\notin G$\".\n\nIf `\\hus` in `not-cdmg` is defined as the specific edge mark pattern \"arrowhead at $j$, tail/blunt at $v$\" (i.e., the directed arrow $v \\to j$ only), then \"$j \\hus v \\notin G$\" by itself excludes only directed edges into $j$ and leaves bidirected edges $v \\leftrightarrow j$ unmentioned by the formal clause — even though the surrounding prose intends them excluded. A literal reader who keys off the formal expression rather than the prose could conclude that a bidirected edge $j \\leftrightarrow v$ is permitted. The colon construction \"no arrowheads pointing towards them: $j \\hus v \\notin G$\" presents the formal expression as the formalization of the prose, but they may not coincide depending on how `\\hus` is defined.\nEND_SUBTLETY",
        "session": "75306b3c-1251-47a4-8bc2-eff541485d1b"
      }
    },
