      "addition_to_the_LN": "[self_membership_notes_require_length_zero_walks] In the definitions of $\\Anc^G(v)$, $\\Desc^G(v)$, $\\Sc^G(v)$, and $\\Dist^G(v)$, the directed and bidirected walks are understood to include the trivial walk of length $0$ consisting of the single vertex $v$ with no edges. Consequently, $v \\in \\Anc^G(v)$, $v \\in \\Desc^G(v)$, $v \\in \\Sc^G(v)$, and $v \\in \\Dist^G(v)$ hold for every $v \\in V$ unconditionally, regardless of whether any edge (in particular any self-loop) incident to $v$ exists in $G$.\n\n[type_mismatch_individual_vs_set_versions] The preamble should read \"$v, w \\in J \\cup V$\" rather than \"$v, w \\in V$\": the individual definitions $\\Pa^G(v)$, $\\Ch^G(v)$, $\\Sib^G(v)$, $\\Anc^G(v)$, $\\Desc^G(v)$, $\\Sc^G(v)$, and $\\Dist^G(v)$ are defined for any $v \\in J \\cup V$, using the same set-builder expressions given. In particular, input nodes ($v \\in J$) may have children, descendants, etc., and the set-version definitions $\\Pa^G(A) := \\bigcup_{v \\in A} \\Pa^G(v)$ (and analogously for the other operators) are well-typed for $A \\ins J \\cup V$ because each summand is defined.\n\n[district_walk_indexing_ambiguous_for_small_n] $w \\in \\Dist^G(v)$ iff there exists a walk from $v$ to $w$ in $G$ in which every edge is bidirected ($\\huh$). The walk may have any length $\\geq 0$; in particular, the length-$0$ walk at $v$ witnesses $v \\in \\Dist^G(v)$, so neither a bidirected self-loop at $v$ nor a length-$2$ bidirected cycle through $v$ is required. The intermediate-node indexing $v_1, \\ldots, v_{n-1}$ in the displayed formula should be read as syntactic sugar for \"walk consisting of bidirected edges\" and imposes no lower bound on walk length.",
      "wording_check": {
        "done": true,
        "output": "I have enough context. Let me audit the tex block now.\n\nKey facts I've confirmed:\n- def_3_1 (CDMG): `E ⊆ (J ∪ V) × V` with no self-loop restriction → **directed self-loops are allowed on V**; `L` explicitly forbids bidirected self-loops.\n- def_3_2: \"$v \\in G$\" means $v \\in J \\cup V$.\n- def_3_4 (Walks): directed/bidirected walks both allow `n ≥ 0`; trivial walks (single node) are explicitly admitted.\n\nNow I'll produce my report.\n\n```\nSUBTLETY:\nid: single_vertex_defs_typed_V_but_set_versions_iterate_over_A_in_JV\nexplanation: The intro declares \"$v,w \\in V$ and $A \\ins J \\cup V$\",\ntyping $v$ as an output node. Every single-vertex definition\n($\\Pa^G(v)$, $\\Ch^G(v)$, $\\Sib^G(v)$, $\\Anc^G(v)$, $\\Desc^G(v)$,\n$\\Sc^G(v)$, $\\Dist^G(v)$) is therefore literally only stated for\n$v \\in V$. But the set-versions invoke the single-vertex definition on\n$v$ ranging over $A$, which may include nodes from $J$, e.g.\n\"$\\Pa^G(A):= \\bigcup_{v \\in A} \\Pa^G(v)$\".\n\nThe formula extends naturally — $\\Pa^G(j)$ for $j \\in J$ would just be\n$\\emptyset$ since the CDMG axiom $E \\ins (J\\cup V) \\times V$ forbids\nincoming edges into $J$ — but the LN never explicitly extends the\nsingle-vertex defs to $J$. A formalizer who types $\\Pa^G, \\Ch^G$ etc.\nstrictly as functions on $V$ will hit a domain mismatch in the set\nversions, and a corresponding cast/extension decision will need to be\nmade silently.\nEND_SUBTLETY\n\nSUBTLETY:\nid: directed_self_loop_makes_v_own_parent_child\nexplanation: Per def_3_1, $E \\ins (J \\cup V) \\times V$ with no\nself-loop exclusion, so a directed self-loop $v \\tuh v$ on an output\nnode $v \\in V$ is *allowed* in a CDMG. (Only bidirected self-loops are\nforbidden, via \"$(v_1,v_2) \\in L \\implies v_1 \\neq v_2$\".)\n\nReading literally, \"$\\Pa^G(v):=\\lC w \\in G\\,|\\, w \\tuh v \\in G \\rC$\"\nthen puts $v \\in \\Pa^G(v)$ whenever $v \\tuh v \\in E$, and likewise\n$v \\in \\Ch^G(v)$. The commented-out alternative for the set version,\n\"%maybe better for sets (???) :$\\Pa^G(A):=(\\bigcup_{v \\in A}\\Pa^G(v))\n\\sm A$. but then if $v \\tuh v \\in E$ then $v \\notin \\Pa^G(\\{v\\}) \\neq\n\\Pa^G(v) \\ni v$\", shows the author was aware of this corner case and\ndeliberately chose the inclusive form so that $\\Pa^G(\\{v\\}) = \\Pa^G(v)$.\n\nWorth surfacing because (a) downstream claims that quietly assume\n\"parents are distinct from the node\" would silently fail under a CDMG\nwith a directed self-loop, and (b) the LN never states anywhere\nwhether CDMGs in practice allow directed self-loops — so the formal\nencoding has to face the question head-on.\nEND_SUBTLETY\n\nSUBTLETY:\nid: anc_desc_dist_self_inclusion_relies_on_trivial_walk_convention\nexplanation: The notes \"$v \\in \\Anc^G(v)$\", \"$v \\in \\Desc^G(v)$\",\n\"$v \\in \\Dist^G(v)$\" only hold because def_3_4 admits the trivial\nwalk (length $n = 0$, a single node) as a valid directed and\nbidirected walk. The notation used here, e.g.\n\"$\\exists$ directed walk: $w \\tuh \\cdots \\tuh v$\" and\n\"$\\exists$ bidirected walk: $v \\huh v_1 \\huh \\cdots \\huh v_{n-1}\n\\huh w$\", *visually* suggests at least one edge — there is no\nexplicit \"$v=w$ counts trivially\" escape hatch within def_3_5's text.\n\nFor the bidirected case this is load-bearing: since CDMG forbids\nbidirected self-loops ($v \\huh v$ never holds), the *only* way for\n$v \\in \\Dist^G(v)$ to be true is the $n=0$ trivial walk. A reader (or\nformalizer) who interprets the \"$v \\huh v_1 \\huh \\cdots \\huh v_{n-1}\n\\huh w$\" notation as requiring at least one edge would derive\n$\\Dist^G(v) = \\emptyset$ in extreme cases (e.g. a graph with no\nbidirected edges incident to $v$), contradicting the stated note.\nThe note is correct only under the def_3_4 reading that includes the\ntrivial walk.\nEND_SUBTLETY\n\nSUBTLETY:\nid: district_walk_notation_does_not_quantify_n\nexplanation: Compare the district's walk notation\n\"$\\exists \\text{ bidirected walk: } v \\huh v_1 \\huh \\cdots \\huh\nv_{n-1} \\huh w$\" with def_3_4's bidirected walk\n\"$v=v_0 \\huh v_1 \\huh \\cdots \\huh v_{n-1} \\huh v_n=w$, for some\n$n \\ge 0$\". The def_3_5 version (a) does not name $v_0$ and $v_n$\n(uses $v$ and $w$ directly), and (b) crucially *does not quantify\n$n$ at all*.\n\nThe notation is awkward for small $n$: for $n = 0$ (trivial walk),\nthe indexed sequence \"$v_1 \\huh \\cdots \\huh v_{n-1}$\" is vacuous and\nthe visible \"$v \\huh w$\" piece is misleading; for $n = 1$ we get\n\"$v_{n-1} = v_0$\" which doesn't appear in the indexing (which starts\nat $v_1$). The reader must mentally cross-reference def_3_4 to figure\nout the intended quantification.\n\nSame concern (notation-without-quantifier) applies to\n\"$\\exists \\text{ directed walk: } w \\tuh \\cdots \\tuh v$\" in\n$\\Anc^G(v)$ and the dual in $\\Desc^G(v)$, though the absence of\nindexed intermediates there makes the ambiguity slightly milder.\nEND_SUBTLETY\n```",
        "session": "381d7ac3-49eb-4a6d-94f3-cea07a358421"
