      },
      "tex_block": "\\begin{defmark}\n\\begin{Def}[Acyclicity]\n    \\label{def-acylic}\n    A  CDMG  $G=(J,V,E,L)$  is called \\emph{acyclic} if there does not exist\n    any non-trivial directed walk from $v$ to itself in $G$ for any node $v \\in G$.\n\\end{Def}\n\\end{defmark}",
      "agent_registry": [
        {
          "kind": "for_website",
          "spawned_by": "manager",
          "session_id": "bc63063e-9499-4fb5-8947-24bc3ba1cd71",
          "first_seen": "2026-06-03T06:56:28+00:00",
          "last_used": "2026-06-03T06:56:28+00:00"
        }
      ],
      "time_needed_to_solve": 1770,
      "addition_to_the_LN": "[nontrivial_directed_walk_not_defined_in_block] A non-trivial directed walk is a directed walk $v_0 \\tuh \\cdots \\tuh v_n$ with $n \\ge 1$ (i.e., one that traverses at least one edge); the trivial walk consisting of a single node $v_0$ is excluded. In particular, a self-loop $v \\tuh v$ constitutes a non-trivial directed walk from $v$ to itself, so an acyclic CDMG contains no self-loops on any $v \\in V$.",
      "wording_check": {
        "done": true,
        "output": "Now I have enough context. Let me analyze the def_3_6 tex block against def_3_4 (Walks) and def_3_1 (CDMG).\n\n```\nSUBTLETY:\nid: non_trivial_qualifier_depends_on_def_3_4\nexplanation: The block says \"there does not exist any non-trivial directed\nwalk from $v$ to itself\", but never defines \"non-trivial\" within this block.\nThe qualifier is essential: per def_3_4 item 2, \"A directed walk from v to\nw in G is of the form: v=v_0 → v_1 → ... → v_n=w, for some n ≥ 0\", and per\nitem 1, \"the trivial walk consisting of a single node v_0 ∈ G is allowed\n(if v=w)\". So the trivial directed walk (n=0) from v to itself always\nexists for every node. Without the \"non-trivial\" qualifier, every CDMG\nwould be non-acyclic. The reader must pick up the \"trivial walk\" terminology\nfrom def_3_4 and apply its negation here. Note also that def_3_4 has a\ncommented-out line \"% Directed walks exclude the trivial walk per\ndefinition.\" — the author considered carving the trivial walk out of the\n\"directed walk\" notion entirely but did not. So in def_3_6 the carve-out\nis delegated to the \"non-trivial\" qualifier. A downstream Lean formalization\nneeds to interpret \"non-trivial\" as \"n ≥ 1\" (i.e., the walk has at least\none edge).\nEND_SUBTLETY\nSUBTLETY:\nid: node_membership_v_in_g_informal\nexplanation: The block writes \"for any node $v \\in G$\", but per def_3_1\n$G = (J, V, E, L)$ is a tuple, not a set, so \"$v \\in G$\" is not literally\nwell-defined. The natural reading (and the convention used in def_3_4's\npreamble \"Let $G=(J,V,E,L)$ be a CDMG and $v,w \\in G$\") is $v \\in V \\cup J$,\ni.e., the disjoint union of input and output nodes. This matters because\nJ-nodes are quantified over too, yet per def_3_1 directed edges satisfy\n$E \\subseteq (J \\cup V) \\times V$ — J-nodes can never be a *target* of a\ndirected edge. Hence no non-trivial directed walk can end at a J-node, and\nthe acyclicity condition is vacuous for $v \\in J$. Whether the author\nintended to quantify only over output nodes $V$ (since J-nodes trivially\nsatisfy the property) or over all nodes (with vacuous coverage of J) is\nleft implicit. A downstream proof that uses acyclicity to derive a\ntopological order, or to drop the last node of a cycle into a particular\nset, could be sensitive to this distinction.\nEND_SUBTLETY\nSUBTLETY:\nid: directed_self_loops_not_excluded\nexplanation: The block treats \"non-trivial directed walk from $v$ to itself\"\nas the obstruction to acyclicity. Per def_3_4 item 2, a directed walk of\nlength $n=1$ is of the form $v = v_0 \\tuh v_1 = v$, i.e., a single directed\nedge from $v$ to itself. Per def_3_1, the bidirected edge set $L$ is\nexplicitly irreflexive (\"$(v_1,v_2) \\in L \\implies v_1 \\neq v_2$\"), but\nthe directed edge set $E \\subseteq (J \\cup V) \\times V$ carries no analogous\nrestriction. So directed self-loops $(v,v) \\in E$ for $v \\in V$ are\npermitted by def_3_1, and any CDMG containing one is automatically\nnon-acyclic by def_3_6. This is consistent with standard graph theory but\nis a corner case worth noting: a CDMG with a single directed self-loop\nand no other edges is \"cyclic\" under this definition. The asymmetric\ntreatment of $E$ vs $L$ in def_3_1 (where $L$ excludes self-loops but $E$\ndoes not) means downstream claims about acyclicity must accommodate\nlength-1 closed directed walks, not just length-≥-2 cycles through\ndistinct vertices.\nEND_SUBTLETY\n```",
        "session": "603efd07-a4e9-4fad-b86a-6bbf5e2a637b"
      }
    },
