      "tex_block": "\\begin{defmark}\n\\begin{Def}\n    A  Conditional Directed Mixed Graph (CDMG)  $G=(J,V,E,L)$  is called:\n   \\begin{enumerate}\n       \\item Conditional Acyclic Directed Mixed Graph (CADMG) if $G$ is acyclic.\n       \\item Directed Mixed Graph (DMG) if $J = \\emptyset$.\n       \\item Acyclic Directed Mixed Graph (ADMG) if $G$ is acyclic and $J = \\emptyset$.\n       \\item Conditional Directed Graph (CDG) if $L = \\emptyset$.\n       \\item Directed Graph (DG) if $J = \\emptyset$ and $L = \\emptyset$.\n       \\item Conditional Directed Acyclic Graph (CDAG) if $G$ is acyclic and $L = \\emptyset$.\n       \\item Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) if $G$ is acyclic, $J=\\emptyset$ and $L = \\emptyset$.\n   \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{Def}\n\\end{defmark}",
      "agent_registry": [
        {
          "kind": "for_website",
          "spawned_by": "manager",
          "session_id": "ac17e944-a780-480f-b492-312c5809ae20",
          "first_seen": "2026-06-03T07:36:35+00:00",
          "last_used": "2026-06-03T07:36:35+00:00"
        }
      ],
      "time_needed_to_solve": 2016,
      "addition_to_the_LN": "",
      "wording_check": {
        "done": true,
        "output": "Now I have enough context. Let me analyze the subtleties in def_3_7's wording.\n\nThe text defines 7 named graph types via the pattern \"A CDMG is called X if Y\", using three independent constraints:\n- (a) G is acyclic\n- (b) J = ∅\n- (c) L = ∅\n\nItems 3, 5, 6, 7 are conjunctions of items 1, 2, 4. This creates overlapping predicates: any CDMG satisfying all three constraints simultaneously is literally called by all 7 names. Combined with def_3_1 (which allows J = V = ∅), the empty graph trivially satisfies all 7.\n\n```\nSUBTLETY:\nid: subtypes_are_overlapping_predicates_not_partition\nexplanation: The seven named subtypes are defined as overlapping predicates on a single CDMG, not as a partition. The pattern \"A CDMG G=(J,V,E,L) is called X if Y\" attaches a name X to G whenever Y holds, with no clause asserting that names are mutually exclusive. The three atomic constraints (G acyclic; J = ∅; L = ∅) are independent, and items 3, 5, 6, 7 are conjunctions of items 1, 2, 4. Consequently a CDMG with G acyclic, J = ∅, L = ∅ literally satisfies all 7 conditions simultaneously: it is at once a CADMG (G acyclic ✓), DMG (J = ∅ ✓), ADMG (G acyclic and J = ∅ ✓), CDG (L = ∅ ✓), DG (J = ∅ and L = ∅ ✓), CDAG (G acyclic and L = ∅ ✓), and DAG (all three ✓). Since def_3_1 explicitly allows J = V = ∅, even the empty graph qualifies for all 7 names. A reader expecting these to be exclusive categories (i.e. a graph is \"a DAG\" rather than also \"an ADMG\") would be misled. Downstream this matters: if a later claim/proof says \"let G be an ADMG\", the literal reading admits G being a DAG; conversely \"if G is a CDMG, exactly one of the following holds\" would be false. This is standard inclusive lattice taxonomy (DAG ⊆ ADMG ⊆ DMG ⊆ CDMG, DAG ⊆ CDAG ⊆ CDG ⊆ CDMG, etc.), but the text never states the inclusion structure or the predicate (vs. distinct-type) intent.\nEND_SUBTLETY\n\nSUBTLETY:\nid: conditional_and_mixed_prefixes_dont_constrain_components\nexplanation: The naming uses suggestive prefixes that the literal definitions do not enforce. \"Conditional\" in CADMG, CDG, CDAG conventionally signals a non-empty conditioning set J, but each definition only states the OTHER constraints — none requires J ≠ ∅. So a CDMG with J = ∅ and G acyclic literally satisfies \"Conditional Acyclic Directed Mixed Graph (CADMG) if G is acyclic\": this graph is non-conditional in the colloquial sense yet bears the \"Conditional\" label. Symmetrically, \"Mixed\" in CDMG/CADMG/DMG/ADMG suggests both directed (E) and bidirected (L) edges are present, but L = ∅ is never excluded — a \"Directed Mixed Graph\" can have no bidirected edges at all (which would normally just be called a directed graph). The text does not warn the reader that the suggestive prefixes are upper-bound categorizations rather than component requirements; a reader taking the names literally may assume e.g. J ≠ ∅ when a claim says \"let G be a CADMG\", leading to subtly stronger hypotheses than the definition actually provides.\nEND_SUBTLETY\n```",
        "session": "f69dce70-278a-447a-9110-a2031778b0fc"
      }
    },
