        "accept_deviation": 0,
        "register_ln_subtlety": 0,
        "no_action": 0
      },
      "tex_block": "\\begin{defmark}\n\\begin{Def}[Topological order]\n    Let $G=(J,V,E,L)$ be a CDMG.\n    A \\emph{topological order} of $G$ is a total order $<$ of $J \\cup V$ such that for all $v,w \\in G$:\n    \\[ v \\in \\Pa^G(w) \\; \\implies \\; v < w.\\]\n    Equivalently, it can be described as an indexing of the nodes $J \\cup V = \\{v_1,\\dots,v_K\\}$ where parents always precede their children.\n\\end{Def}\n\\end{defmark}",
      "agent_registry": [
        {
          "kind": "for_website",
          "spawned_by": "manager",
          "session_id": "d03f82aa-33ee-42c0-b50d-d0e81b114d2c",
          "first_seen": "2026-06-03T08:13:57+00:00",
          "last_used": "2026-06-03T08:13:57+00:00"
        }
      ],
      "time_needed_to_solve": 2116,
      "addition_to_the_LN": "",
      "wording_check": {
        "done": true,
        "output": "Looking at the tex block for def_3_8 (Topological order):\n\nThe definition is clean and standard:\n- A total order `<` on `J ∪ V`\n- Constraint: `v ∈ Pa^G(w) ⟹ v < w` (parents precede children)\n- Plus an equivalent reformulation as an indexing `{v_1, ..., v_K}`\n\nChecking for potential issues:\n\n1. **`for all v, w ∈ G`** — technically `G = (J,V,E,L)` is a tuple, so `v ∈ G` is sloppy notation for `v ∈ J ∪ V`. But this is universal abuse-of-notation in graph theory and the intent is unambiguous.\n\n2. **Corner cases** — empty `J ∪ V`: vacuously satisfied; singleton: trivial; cyclic graph: no topological order exists (the definition correctly returns an empty set of valid orders); self-loops: would require `v < v` which fails under strict order, again correctly preventing a topological order.\n\n3. **Equivalence between the two descriptions** — relies on finiteness of `J ∪ V` (indexing by `{1,...,K}`), but finiteness of CDMG node sets is standard in this framework.\n\n4. **Bidirected edges (`L`)** — impose no ordering constraint, since only `Pa^G` (directed parents) appears in the implication. This is intentional and standard.\n\n5. **Strict vs non-strict order** — the `<` notation conventionally denotes strict; consistent with the parent-precedes-child reading.\n\nNo genuine ambiguity, unintended corner case, internal inconsistency, or under-specification.\n\n```\nNO_SUBTLETIES\n```",
        "session": "a8664ffc-33b8-4361-b4f0-ff74284569d9"
      }
