      "wording_check": {
        "done": true,
        "output": "I'll audit the LN tex block for claim_3_2 along with its citing definitions (acyclicity, topological order, CDMG) to ground the subtlety analysis.\n\nSUBTLETY:\nid: claim_finiteness_not_stated_but_required_by_def_3_8\nexplanation: The claim says simply \"A CDMG $G=(J,V,E,L)$ is acyclic if and only if it has a topological order.\" with no hypothesis on the size of $J \\cup V$. CDMGs (def_3_1) are not required to be finite. However, the definition of topological order this claim is built on (def_3_8) gives two formulations of the same notion:\n\n  1. a total order $<$ on $J \\cup V$ with $v \\in \\Pa^G(w) \\implies v < w$, and\n  2. \"an indexing of the nodes $J \\cup V = \\{v_1,\\dots,v_K\\}$ where parents always precede their children.\"\n\nThe second formulation literally requires $J \\cup V$ to be enumerable as $\\{v_1,\\dots,v_K\\}$ — i.e. finite with cardinality $K$. The claim never says \"finite CDMG\", so a literal reader is left to wonder which formulation it is asserting equivalence to. The forward direction of the lemma (acyclic ⟹ topological order exists), interpreted under formulation (1), is the Szpilrajn extension theorem in the infinite case and relies on the Axiom of Choice (or is genuinely false in choice-free settings). Under formulation (2), the lemma fails outright as soon as $J \\cup V$ is infinite, because no infinite set admits an indexing $\\{v_1,\\dots,v_K\\}$. Either the claim implicitly assumes finiteness — in which case the statement should say so — or it doesn't, in which case the proof must specify which definition of topological order it is using and invoke AC. Downstream, any claim that pulls \"the topological order $v_1 < \\dots < v_K$ on $J \\cup V$\" out of acyclicity (a very common pattern, e.g. induction on a topological index) is silently using the finite reading.\nEND_SUBTLETY\n\nSUBTLETY:\nid: has_a_topological_order_existence_vs_equipment\nexplanation: The phrase \"it has a topological order\" is slightly under-specified. Read literally, \"has\" could mean either (a) \"there exists at least one topological order on $G$\" or (b) \"$G$ comes equipped with a distinguished topological order\". The intended reading is plainly (a) — topological orders are not unique, and \"is acyclic\" is a property of the bare graph, not of any extra structure — but the tex never spells this out. The corresponding Lean encoding has to make this an existential, not a structure field. A reader who instead encoded \"has\" as a structural component (a CDMG-with-topological-order) would render the biconditional trivial in one direction and ill-typed in the other.\nEND_SUBTLETY",
        "session": "6a1a85c1-0141-4e1c-83df-9ac9131e7e23"
      }
