      },
      "tex_block": "\\begin{claimmark}\n\\begin{Lem}[Two disjoint node-splittings commute]\n   Let $G=(J,V,E,L)$ be a CDMG and $W_1, W_2 \\ins V$ two disjoint subsets of the output nodes of $G$.\n   Then the CDMG obtained from first node-splitting $W_1$ and then node-splitting $W_2$ is the same CADMG that arises from first node-splitting $W_2$ and then node-splitting $W_1$:\n   \\[ \\lp G_{\\spl(W_1)} \\rp_{\\spl(W_2)} =  \\lp G_{\\spl(W_2)} \\rp_{\\spl(W_1)}  =  G_{\\spl(W_1 \\dcup W_2)}.   \\]\n\\end{Lem}\n\\end{claimmark}",
      "agent_registry": [],
      "time_needed_to_solve": 0,
      "addition_to_the_LN": "[cdmg_vs_cadmg_terminology_mismatch] The term \"CADMG\" appearing in the statement is a typographical inconsistency and should be read as \"CDMG\". The node-splitting operation $\\spl(\\cdot)$ takes a CDMG to a CDMG, so both iterated splittings $\\lp G_{\\spl(W_1)} \\rp_{\\spl(W_2)}$ and $\\lp G_{\\spl(W_2)} \\rp_{\\spl(W_1)}$, as well as $G_{\\spl(W_1 \\dcup W_2)}$, are CDMGs, and the asserted equality is an equality of CDMGs."
    },
